  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
        <div xml:id="KT161-kilavi">
          <p type="edition">iravukkuṟikkaṇ vanta talaimakaṉaik kāppu mikutiyāṉ etirpaṭap peṟāta talaimakaḷ piṟṟaiñāṉṟu talaimakaṉ ciṟaipuṟattāṉākat tōḻikkuc colluvāḷāyc colliyatu.</p>
          <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">She speaking as if speaking to the confidante, while HE is behind the hedge at a later time, [that is, she] who had not managed, because of the number of guards, to appear near HIM who had come to the night tryst.</p>
          </div>


        <div xml:id="KT161">
            <lg type="edition">
<l>                poḻutu melliṉṟu peyalu mōvātu</l>
<l>                kaḻutukaṇ paṉippa vīcu mataṉṟalaip</l>
<l>                pulippaṟ ṟālip putalvarp pulli</l>
<l>                yaṉṉā veṉṉu maṉṉaiyu maṉṉō</l>
<l>                veṉmalain taṉaṉko ṟāṉē taṉmalai</l>
<l>                yāra nāṟu mārpiṉaṉ</l>
<l>                māri yāṉaiyiṉ vantuniṉ ṟaṉaṉē.</l>
             </lg>
            <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
           <l>Time without light and the rain, incessantly,</l>
           <l rend="indent">splashing to make demons' eyes quiver,</l>
           <l rend="indent4">and on top of that<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">ataṉ-talai</term> should be analysed as the oblique of the demonstrative pronoun + <term xml:lang="ta">talai</term> as a pointed locative "on top of that" = "moreover" (thus also Cām.).</note>,</l>
           <l>mother who<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">eṉṉum</term> could equally well be a habitual future: "Mother keeps saying ...".</note> says “mother!”, holding tight</l>
           <l rend="indent">the son with [his] tiger-tooth amulet(?).</l>
           <l rend="indent4">Alas!</l>
           <l>Was he opposed to me?<note place="foot">The question <term xml:lang="ta">eṉ malaintaṉaṉ kol</term> is semantically doubtful. One possibility is, as above, to understand <term xml:lang="ta">malai-tal</term> = DEDR 4741 "to be opposed, fight against" with <term xml:lang="ta">eṉ</term> as oblique of the personal pronoun 1st sg., that is, to understand a question on HER part as to whether HE had been angry with her for not turning up. The other possibility for <term xml:lang="ta">malai-tal</term> is DEDR 4736 "to be staggered, doubtful, confused". If we take <term xml:lang="ta">eṉ</term> as the interrogative pronoun in a weak sense here, we could also read the question as: "was he confused?", which seems to be Cām.'s (and TVG's) view of the matter.</note></l>
           <l rend="indent2">He,</l>
           <l rend="indent">with a chest fragrant from sandal paste of his mountain,</l>
           <l rend="indent">like an elephant in a shower,</l>
           <l rend="indent3">came [and] stood [there].</l>


            </lg>
        </div>
